com.steelypip.powerups.minxml

Class FlexiMinXML

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.steelypip.powerups.minxml.AbsMinXML
      • com.steelypip.powerups.minxml.AbsFlexiMinXML
        • com.steelypip.powerups.minxml.FlexiMinXML
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    MinXML, java.lang.Iterable<MinXML>, java.util.Collection<MinXML>, java.util.List<MinXML>

    public class FlexiMinXML
extends AbsFlexiMinXML
    This implementation provides a full implementation of all the mandatory and optional methods of the MinXML interface. It aims to strike a balance between fast access, update and reasonable compactness in the most important cases. A TreeMap is used to track attributes and an ArrayList to track children; these provide good performance at the expense of space. However, when there are no attributes the TreeMap is not allocated and when there are no children the ArrayList is not allocated; these two cases are so common that the reduction in space is (typically) significant.

      • trimToSize

        public void trimToSize()
        Description copied from interface: MinXML
        This method signals that there will be no further updates to an element, at least for a while, and the implementation should consider this a good opportunity to compact the space used by this element and all child elements, including any shared elements. Implementations must be clear on whether any subsequent updates are allowed or forbidden. If subsequent updates are forbidden, the implementation must throw an IllegalStateException.
        Specified by:
        trimToSize in interface MinXML
